 for bestpractices and # Terms of Service Page

## Overview
Create a comprehensive Terms of Service (ToS) page for StudySpark that clearly communicates the legal terms governing the use of the platform. This page should cover acceptable use, content ownership, liability limitations, privacy references where relevant, and mechanisms for acceptance during user onboarding. The deliverable includes frontend UI components for rendering the document with accessible navigation, a structured content model suitable for localization, and required hooks to capture user acceptance during sign-up flow. All code should be runtime-safe against null/undefined values and follow the project’s safety rules (Supabase results guarded with data ?? [], array methods guarded, proper useState defaults, etc.).

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A dedicated Terms of Service page for StudySpark that presents legal terms governing usage, with clear sections and navigable structure. It should be accessible via site footer and in-app navigation.

Goals:
- Legally compliant ToS covering:
  - Acceptable use and user responsibilities
  - Content ownership, rights, and license grants
  - Liability limitations and disclaimers
  - Termination and modification policies
  - Privacy references and data handling notes
  - Governing law and dispute resolution
  - contact information and update notices
  - Effective date and versioning
- Provide a clean, readable, and accessible reading experience with quick navigation (table of contents), and an “Accept” mechanism during onboarding or sign-up flows when required.
- Ensure downstream components (onboarding flow, sign-up, modal dialogs) can reference the ToS terms and acceptance state.

Connected features and UI guidance:
- Terms Document: Long-form legal text with hierarchical headings (H1/H2/H3), anchors/IDs for in-page navigation, a table of contents (TOC) sidebar or top anchor list for quick access.
- Accept Button: A prominent, accessible CTA used during first-time sign-up or sign-in flows to indicate agreement. Persist acceptance in user profile (e.g., a boolean flag) and control progression in onboarding.
- Accessibility: Keyboard navigable, screen-reader friendly, proper color contrast per design system.
- Localization: Content model supports future translations; strings pulled from a structured source (e.g., i18n JSON or CMS) with a fallback.
- Versioning: Display current ToS version and effective date; provide change-notice section when updates occur.
- Analytics/Telemetry: Optional events for viewing ToS and accepting, respecting privacy guidelines.
- Security/Privacy: Do not leak sensitive data; acceptance is stored securely and only used for gating onboarding or service access.

UI/Visual guidance from PROJECT CONTEXT:
- Visual style follows StudySpark’s design system: soft pastels, rounded shapes, friendly typography, subtle gradients, and accessible controls.
- Use rounded corners, soft shadows, and card-like sections for readability.
- Navigation should be intuitive: top header with branding, optional side TOC, main content area with clearly separated sections.

API integrations:
- No external API dependencies required for ToS rendering; content may be static or sourced from internal CMS. If content is fetched, ensure safe handling: data ?? [], Array.isArray checks, and robust defaults. If acceptance state is stored, ensure secure endpoints for reading/writing the acceptance flag with proper auth.

## Components to Build
- ToSPageContainer: Layout wrapper with header, TOC, and content area.
  - Props: locale, version, effectiveDate, onAccept callback (optional during onboarding).
- ToSSection: Reusable section component rendering headers, paragraphs, and lists.
  - Props: title, content (array of paragraphs), subsections (optional).
- TableOfContents (TOC): Interactive in-page navigation with anchor links; collapsible?; highlights current section while scrolling.
- AcceptConsentCard (onboarding): Prominent container with summary of terms and an Accept button; includes a secondary Decline/Cancel action for advanced flows if allowed.
- ToSContentRenderer: Renders rich-text-like structured content (headers, paragraphs, lists) safely from a source (static or CMS). Guard all data access with data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks.
- VersionBadge: Small badge showing ToS version and effective date.
- Accessibility-Fixtures: Hidden heading landmarks, skip-to-content, ARIA roles, and keyboard focus management for all interactive elements.
- LocalizationLayer (optional): Strings loader for i18n with fallbacks.

Technical details:
- All content should be structured as an array of sections with titles and content blocks to ease rendering and localization. Example shape:
  sections: [
    { id: 'intro', title: 'Introduction', blocks: [{ type: 'p', text: '...' }, { type: 'ul', items: [...] }] },
    ...
  ]
- The page should render a sticky or fixed-position TOC on wide viewports and a collapsible TOC on smaller viewports if space-constrained.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages/Routes:
  - /terms-of-service (Public access)
  - /onboarding/accept-terms or integrated sign-up flow: workflow to present ToS and require acceptance before proceeding.
- Components:
  - ToSPageContainer: Structure with header, TOC, content.
  - ToSSection, ToSContentRenderer, TableOfContents, AcceptConsentCard, VersionBadge, AccessibilityFixtures.
- Data handling:
  - Load ToS content from a static module or CMS-provided JSON. Ensure you guard with data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks.
  - If using CMS, fetch content using a safe API wrapper; validate response: const sections = Array.isArray(response?.data?.sections) ? response.data.sections : [].
- State management:
  - useState for sections with default []: const [sections, setSections] = useState<Section[]>([]);
  - Use effect to fetch and populate sections; guard all array operations with (sections ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(sections) ? sections.map(...) : [].
  - If implementing acceptance state during onboarding: const [accepted, setAccepted] = useState<boolean>(false); persist in user profile on acceptance.
- Accessibility:
  - Ensure proper ARIA attributes for landmark roles, nav landmarks for TOC, and aria-current for active section.
  - Keyboard focus management for Accept button; ensure skip-to-content link exists.
- Styling:
  - Apply the project’s design system with pastel backgrounds, rounded cards, and typography from the provided palette.
  - Implement responsive layout: On desktop, a two-column layout with a left TOC and right content; on mobile, a single-column flow with a collapsible TOC.
- Interactions:
  - Smooth in-page scrolling to sections when TOC items are clicked.
  - Accept button should be disabled until user scrolls to bottom or user explicitly accepts (design can choose approach; implement a robust optional requirement to scroll-check if needed).
  - On hover/focus visible states; accessible focus rings.

### Backend
- APIs (optional, if ToS content is CMS-driven or needs persistence):
  - GET /api/tos (returns { sections, version, effectiveDate })
  - POST /api/users/:id/accept-tos (body: { version }) to record user acceptance
  - Ensure proper authentication and authorization (e.g., require user to be logged in for acceptance). If ToS is public, ACE acceptance may be gated to onboarding flow only.
- Database schema (optional):
  - Table: tos_versions
    - id (PK)
    - version (string)
    - effective_date (date)
    - content (JSON)
  - Table: user_tos_acceptances
    - id (PK)
    - user_id (FK)
    - tos_version_id (FK)
    - accepted_at (timestamp)

### Integration
- Frontend fetch flow:
  - If content is CMS-driven, fetch from /api/tos; otherwise use local static content.
  - After acceptance (on onboarding), call /api/users/:id/accept-tos to persist acceptance; optimistically update UI and handle rollback if API fails.
- State synchronization:
  - Ensure acceptance state gates onboarding progression; when accepted, navigate to next onboarding step or home.
- Data safety:
  - All API responses validated; use data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks; destructuring with defaults: const { sections = [], version = '', effectiveDate = '' } = response ?? {}.

## User Experience Flow
1. User visits Terms of Service page via footer link or onboarding flow.
2. Page loads: header, TOC, and the long-form content sections render with accessible navigation.
3. User reads content; can use TOC to jump to sections; content sections visibly separated with clear typography.
4. If onboarding flow requires acceptance:
   - User reviews ToS; must click Accept to proceed.
   - On acceptance, the app persists acceptance (via API or local state) and unlocks subsequent onboarding steps.
5. If updates occur:
   - Show a small version badge with the effective date; optionally display a change-notice section.
6. Non-onboarding view:
   - Acceptance state saved; user can revisit the ToS and review changes, but re-acceptance is not required unless terms are updated per policy.

## Technical Specifications
- Data Models: See above; if not using CMS, implement static content model consistent with sections blocks.
- API Endpoints: 
  - GET /api/tos
  - POST /api/users/:id/accept-tos (requires authentication)
- Security:
  - Ensure endpoints that modify state require authentication (e.g., OAuth/JWT session).
  - Do not leak content or acceptance status to unauthorized users.
- Validation:
  - Frontend: validate that acceptance action updates a boolean and, for onboarding, does not proceed until acceptance is recorded.
  - Backend (if implemented): validate payload shape; ensure version matches current version during acceptance; handle race conditions.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The ToS page renders with a responsive two-column layout (TOC + content) on desktop and a single-column flow on mobile.
- [ ] All data accesses are null-safe: uses data ?? [], Array.isArray(...) pattern for rendering section lists, and proper defaults.
- [ ] Content sections render with proper hierarchy: H1/H2/H3, paragraphs, and lists as defined by the data model.
- [ ] There is an accessible Table of Contents with in-page anchors and aria-current highlighting the active section during scroll/navigation.
- [ ] An Accept button exists in onboarding flows; it becomes enabled/functional only after the user interaction requirements are met and persists acceptance on the backend or local state; onboarding proceeds after acceptance.
- [ ] Version badge displays current version and effective date; date formatting is locale-aware.
- [ ] All interactive elements have proper focus management and visual focus indicators.
- [ ] No runtime errors when content is missing or API responses are null.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Ensure consistency with StudySpark’s visual language: soft pastel palette, rounded shapes, friendly iconography, and gentle gradients.
- Maintain legibility with generous white space and clear typographic hierarchy.
- Use pill-shaped badges for labels and rounded number styling for emphasis where appropriate.
- Include subtle hover/active states for cards and navigation elements to convey interactivity.
- Accessibility-first: semantic HTML structure, ARIA labels, and keyboard navigability.

